'''''The Sticking Place''''' is a 2012 interactive web documentary by [http://www.moosestashfilms.com Moosestash Films]. The film explores the journey of elite athlete, [[Leah Callahan]], a freestyle wrestler with a dream to compete in the Olympic Games.<ref name=VancouverObserver>{{cite news|last=Gomez|first=Gisela|title=BC wrestler Leah Callahan's journey to the London Olympics|url=http://www.vancouverobserver.com/node/11779|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=[[Vancouver Observer]]|date=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=Ubyssey>{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Kayi|title=New sports doc allows audience to interact with athlete’s journey|url=http://ubyssey.ca/culture/277new-sports-doc-allows-audience-to-interact-with-athletes-journey/|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=[[The Ubyssey]]|date=4 December 2011}}</ref>
==Story== Following Leah Callahan, the web documentary blends together some of the most candid moments in the wrestler's push to the Olympic Games, presenting her journey through collage, video, animation, photos, audio clips, and user activated/generated content, housed within a collection of vibrant, responsive web-screens. Audiences are invited to explore some of the most intimate details of Leah's day-to-day life, watch her train, read her personal journal entries and emails, share in her childhood home videos, and spend moments with friends and family, all the while examining the realities of what it takes to pursue an Olympic-sized dream.<ref name=MetroNews>{{cite news|last=Nolais|first=Jeremy|title=Interactive film follows Calgary wrestler on road to Olympics|url=http://metronews.ca/news/calgary/253365/interactive-film-follows-calgary-wrestler-on-road-to-olympics/|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=[[Metro News (Calgary)]]|date=7 June 2012}}</ref>
==Production== Vancouver-based filmmakers Josephine Anderson and Brittany Baxter co-directed/produced the film, following and filming Callahan over the span of a year in Edmonton, Calgary, Winnipeg, Mackenzie and Prince George.<ref name=VancouverSun>{{cite news|last=Bell|first=Terry|title=Wrestler Leah Callahan's journey captured in web documentary|url=https://vancouversun.com/sports/Wrestler+Leah+Callaghan+journey+captured+documentary/6848301/story.html|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|date=28 June 2012}}</ref> The Sticking Place was produced with assistance from the [[National Film Board of Canada]]'s Filmmaker Assistance Program, and with funds generated from a crowd-funding campaign on [[Kickstarter]].<ref name=NorthShoreNews>{{cite news|last=Duane|first=Rosalind|title=Olympics 2012: Interactive documentary follows Canadian wrestler Leah Callahan to London|url=http://www.nsnews.com/entertainment/movie-guide/Olympic+dream/6998528/story.html|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=[[North Shore News]]|date=27 July 2012}}</ref>
==Release== ''The Sticking Place'' went live online on June 27, 2012. On February 24, 2013, The Sticking Place was awarded a Pixel Award for Best Sports Project, also garnering the People's Champ Award. On November 15, 2012, The Sticking Place was nominated for Best Web Series: Non-Fiction at the Digi Awards in Toronto, formerly known as the Canadian New Media Awards.<ref name="PixelAwards">{{cite news|last=Awards|first=Pixel|title=Announcing the 7th Annual Pixel Awards Winners!|url=http://www.pixelawards.com/nom_win_2012.php#Sports|accessdate=24 February 2013|newspaper=[[Pixel Awards]]|date=24 February 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304085614/http://www.pixelawards.com/nom_win_2012.php#Sports|archivedate=4 March 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name="MediaCaster">{{cite news|last=Caster|first=Media|title=Digi Awards Nominees Revealed in Live Webcast|url=http://www.mediacastermagazine.com/news/digi-awards-nominees-revealed-in-live-webcast/1001860741/|accessdate=21 November 2012|newspaper=[[Mediacaster Magazine]]|date=16 November 2012}}</ref>
